 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=millikinerreene>Millikin Erreene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Arrowbringer </span><br>  Posts: 119<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(12/6/02 5:55:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=708.topic&index=76>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: reply</span><hr size=1> Cyllyan states:  &quot;what's a &quot;tort&quot;?&quot;<br>
<br>
A tort is an act that constitutes a breach of contract or agreement or causes harm to another party that may make the individual/group who commits the tort subject to liability for injury and/or damages.  A tort may or may not be expressly illegal but still subjects the person accused of committing it to the possibility of a lawsuit.  They're defined and punished by state law or state interpretation as opposed to federal law or in some cases, common sense.<br>
<br>
The aforementioned case of the woman suing McDonalds for making the coffee too hot is a tort.  There's no actual legislation regulating coffee temperature but the argument is that McDonald's was negilgent about their patrons' safety by not displaying a warning about their coffee being hot.  Common sense would dictate that the woman should have known the coffee was hot (And had the case been tried in another state, that may well have been the verdict.) But in the state where the case was heard, guilt/innocence of a tort violation is determined by whether or not the party was injured and the accused was/was not responsible for the act.<br>
<br>
<br>
M. E.<br>
